{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":27581,"record_hash":"sha256:0733ff474a78536d9711ebcdac323b7908a84d99bb06ed4184529fbf80084ba8","timestamp":"2026-05-11T12:06:43.068Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"I think that instinct is right. For the two use cases, we probably want a **human/agent-readable working timeline**, not a faithful mirror of every provider bookkeeping event.\n\nMy pragmatic take:\n\n| Bucket | Keep? | Why |\n|---|---|---|\n| `message` | Yes | Core for both handoff and review. This is the conversation. |\n| `tool_call` | Yes | Useful context: what commands/files/tools the agent used. |\n| `tool_result` | Yes, but prune duplication | Useful evidence: tests, errors, command output. But we should not store the same output in both `text` and `source_record.payload.output`. |\n| `session` | Probably no transcript rows | Use it to populate session/source metadata, but don’t append repeated `session_meta` records. Repeated base instructions/dynamic tools are noisy and expensive. |\n| `other` | Mostly no | Token counts, turn context, compaction, lifecycle events, spawn/wait events are provider mechanics. Low value for handoff/review. |\n\nSo I’d move toward this rule:\n\n```text\nStore transcript records only for:\n- message\n- tool_call\n- tool_result\n\nUse session/other records only for metadata extraction when needed.\n```\n\nThen add one small pruning rule before storing `source_record`:\n\n```text\nIf we copied a field into normalized `text` or `tool_input`,\nremove that exact provider field from `source_record`.\n```\n\nThat would cut meaningful size without making the POC clever. It also makes the stored timeline more honest: “here is what the user/agent said and what tools ran,” not “here is every internal Codex event.”","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T12:06:43.068Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"mes